   New Securities Issues
</HL>
<DATE>
05/22/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C23
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP UIS FNM GE FORGN G.CBK F
</CO>
<IN>
MORTGAGES, MORTGAGE BANKERS, MORTGAGE-BACKED SECURITIES (MOR)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
BANKS (BNK)
</IN>
<LP>
   The following were among yesterday's offerings and
pricings in U.S. and non-U.S. capital markets, with terms and
syndicate manager, as compiled by Dow Jones Capital Markets
Report:
                                                                                                       

                        CORPORATES
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   Unisys Corp. -- $300 million of credit-sensitive notes,
due July 1, 1997, priced at par to yield 10.30%. The notes
offer bondholders protection in the form of coupon increases
that are triggered when the the company's credit rating is
downgraded by one full category. The noncallable notes were
priced at a spread of 150 basis points above the Treasury's
seven-year note. Rated Baa-3 by Moody's Investors Service
Inc. and triple-B by Standard &amp; Poor's Corp., the issue will
be sold through underwriters led by Bear Stearns &amp; Co.
                                                                                                       

                        MUNICIPALS
                                                                                                       

   Alabama Housing Finance Authority -- $55 million of
single-family mortgage revenue bonds, GNMA collateralized
home mortgage revenue bond program, 1990 Series B, due April
1 and Oct. 1, 1992-2002, 2010, 2021 and 2022, repriced by a
Goldman Sachs &amp; Co. group to lower some yields by five to 10
basis points. The bonds are now priced to yield from 6.40% in
1992 to 7.90% in 2022, changed from a yield of 6.50% in 1992
to 7.95% in 2022. Current interest serial bonds are now
priced at par to yield from 6.40% in 1992 to 7.25% in 2002,
changed from priced at par to yield from 6.50% in 1992 to
7.35% in 2002. There are $7.74 million of 7.80% term bonds
priced at par in 2010, changed from 7.85% at par due Oct. 1,
2010. There are $14.5 million of 7.60% term bonds priced at
par due Oct. 1, 2021, which are unchanged. There are $27.41
million of 7.90% term bonds priced at par in 2022, changed
from 7.95% issues at par, due Oct. 1, 2022. The bonds are
rated triple-A by S&amp;P. Interest on the bonds will be treated
as a preference item in calculating the Federal alternative
minimum tax that may be imposed on certain investors.

                      MORTGAGE-BACKED
                                                                                                       

   Federal National Mortgage Association -- $300 million of
Remic mortgage securities, offered in 10 classes by Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc. The offering, Series 1990-69, is backed by
Fannie Mae 9 1/2% securities.
   Federal National Mortgage Association -- $200 million of
Remic mortgage securities, offered in five classes by B.T.
Securities, the securities unit of Bankers Trust New York
Corp. The offering, Series 1990-70, is backed by
principal-only securities from Fannie Mae strips offerings.
That collateral consists of $130 million (face amount) of
principalonly strips from Fannie Mae's strips trust 11, which
is backed by Fannie Mae 9% securities, and $70 million of
principal only strips from Fannie Mae's trust 58 strips deal,
which is backed by 9 1/2% securities.
                                                                                                       

                         EUROBONDS
                                                                                                       

   Export-Import bank (Japan) -- $200 million of 9 1/2%
Eurobonds due June 29, 2000, priced at 101 1/2 to yield
9.63%, via IBJ International Ltd.
   General Electric Capital Corp. (U.S) -- 100 million
Canadian dollars of 13% Eurobonds due June 18, 1992, priced
at 101 1/2, via Bankers Trust International.
   European Investment Bank (agency) -- 125 million European
currency units of 10% fungible Eurobonds due February 14,
1997, via Nikko Securities Ltd. Fungible with an existing Ecu
1 billion issue.
   World Bank (agency) -- 30 billion yen of 6 7/8% Eurobonds
due June 11, 1997, priced at 101 3/8 to yield 6.92% less
fees, via LTCB International. Fees 1 5/8.
   Oesterreichische Kontrollbank AG (Austria) -- 150 million
Swiss francs of 7 1/4% public bonds due June 29, 2005, priced
at 101, via Swiss Bank Corp. Guarantee by the Republic of
Austria. Call from June 29, 2000 at 101 1/2, declining by 1/2
point per year.
   Swedish Export Credit (Sweden) -- 300 million Swedish
kronor of 13 5/8% bonds due June 21, 1993, priced at 101.20
to yield 13.70% less fees, via Skandinaviska Enskilda Banken.
Fees 1 3/8.
   Commerzbank Overseas Finance NV (W. German parent) -- 150
billion of 12 5/8% Eurobonds priced at 101.4 to yield 12.70%c
less fees, via Banco di Roma. Guaranteed by Commerzbank AG.
Fees 1 5/8.
   Interfinance Credit National (French parent) -- 500
million French francs of 10 1/4% Eurobonds due May 21, 1993,
priced at 101 3/8, via Credit Commercial de France. Fungible
with a 500 million franc issue outstanding. Guaranteed by
Credit National.
   Ford Capital BV (U.S. parent) -- 150 million pounds of 13
3/8% Eurobonds due June 12, 1997, priced at 101 5/8, via JP
Morgan Securities Ltd. Offered at a fixed price of par.
Guaranteed by Ford Motor Co., the parent company.
   ---
   Corrections &amp; Amplifications

   COMMERZBANK OVERSEAS FINANCE N.V. offered 150 billion lira
of 12 5/8% Eurobonds priced at 101.4 to yield 12.70% less
fees. In yesterday's edition the denomination of the
Eurobonds was omitted.
   (WSJ May 23, 1990)
