<HL>
   Credit Ratings
</HL>
<DATE>
05/22/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C23
</SO>
<CO>
   GQ STK T UIS
</CO>
<IN>
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
</IN>
<LP>
   AMERICAN TELEPHONE &amp; TELEGRAPH Co. (New York) -- Standard
&amp; Poor's Corp. said it affirmed its ratings on $11.1 billion
of debt issued by this telecommunications concern and two of
its units. The rating concern affirmed its double-A rating on
AT&amp;T's senior unsecured debt, which accounted for most of the
$11.1 billion, and single-A-1-plus on commercial paper; and
single-A-1-plus on commercial paper issued by AT&amp;T Capital
Corp. and AT&amp;T Credit Corp. S&amp;P's move came almost a month
after Moody's Investors Service Inc. upgraded its rating on
$9.2 billion of AT&amp;T's senior debt to double-A-3 from
single-A-1. Even after the upgrade, Moody's rating on AT&amp;T's
senior debt remains slightly lower than S&amp;P's, which has held
steady at double-A since it was downgraded because of the
1984 breakup of the Bell System; before the breakup, S&amp;P
rated AT&amp;T triple-A. In its affirmation, which came after an
annual review, S&amp;P said financial support for AT&amp;T's credit
is expected to strengthen in the near term to mid-term, as
earnings and cash flow improve. But it also noted that
leverage has increased in the past two years, and that
further investments in the financial sector may weaken AT&amp;T's
balance sheet in the near term.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   GRUMMAN Corp. -- Standard &amp; Poor's Corp. lowered its
ratings on about $510 million of this Bethpage, N.Y.,
concern's senior debt and preferred stock. The ratings firm
reduced its rating on senior debt to triple-B-minus from
triple-B and on subordinated debt and preferred stock to
double-B-plus from triple-B-minus. S&amp;P said the downgrades
reflect "Grumman's weakening competitive position and
continued fairly aggressive debt usage within the context of
deteriorating overall defense industry demand prospects."
Grumman, principally a manufacturer of military aircraft,
declined to comment. S&amp;P said there is "increasing pressure
on Grumman to secure new defense-electronics and
aircraft-remanufacturing business to bolster future
performance. This will become increasingly difficult in a
period of declining military procurement."
   ---
   STORAGE TECHNOLOGY Corp. -- Moody's Investors Service Inc.
said it raised the rating on the Louisville, Colo., company's
13.5% senior debentures to Ba2 from Ba3, affecting about $243
million in debt. The rating concern said it believes the
maker of data-storage devices will report improved results
from sales of its automated cartridge library systems, which
allow dozens of tape cartridges to be accessed quickly.
   ---
   UNISYS Corp. -- Standard &amp; Poors Corp. said it affirmed
its ratings on approximately $4.9 billion of this company's
debt and preferred stock, including its triple-B rating on
senior debt. S&amp;P said the Blue Bell, Pa., computer maker has
experienced an erosion of its balance sheet, but that recent
restructurings should return the company to profitability in
the near term. Still, S&amp;P noted, Unisys's debt-to-capital is
high and its future is uncertain. For those reasons, S&amp;P
said, there is a potential for ratings downgrades.
</TEXT>
