<HL>
   Bank of Boston Corp. Disbands Division
   Specializing in Leveraged Buy-Out Loans
   ----
   By Christopher J. Chipello
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/22/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A8
</SO>
<CO>
   BKB
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   BOSTON -- Bank of Boston Corp., one of the leading bank
lenders for leveraged buy-outs, has quietly disbanded a
division that specialized in such transactions.
   While Bank of Boston has profited in the past from
leveraged transactions, the outlook is cloudier for some of
the recent deals it has helped finance, such as the
acquisitions of G. Heileman Brewing Co., Friendly Ice Cream
and Prime Computer Inc.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The action, which bank spokesmen described as part of an
ongoing reorganization, underlines a growing wariness by
banks toward leveraged buy-outs. Many banks have recently
taken a more conservative approach to these loans -- partly
because of concerns that a slowing economy could spell
trouble for highly leveraged companies, but also because of
pressure from federal regulators and worried investors.
   Peter Manning, Bank of Boston's chief financial officer,
stressed that the bank intends to continue making loans for
so-called highly leveraged transactions, despite the
dissolution of the bank's acquisition-finance division. The
division, which included about 16 officers, made leveraged
buy-out loans to midsized companies that didn't fall into the
bailiwick of the bank's specialized-loan divisions.
   Those specialized divisions will continue to seek
acquisition loans in industries that the bank has
traditionally served, such as cable television, Mr. Manning
said.
   But Mr. Manning acknowledged that the bank's decision last
fall to tighten its criteria for highly leveraged
transactions, had left the acquisition-finance division with
"a thinner net" for landing deals. For example, the bank now
insists on keeping no more than $50 million of any individual
loan, selling off the remaining amount. Previously, the bank
would keep as much as $75 million of a loan.
   Some leveraged buy-out specialists say that, while many
banks have become more conservative about leveraged buy-out
lending, the pattern is particularly marked at Bank of
Boston. The company, in its first quarter earnings report,
noted that it made no new commitments for financing of highly
leveraged transactions during the period. Partly as a result,
the bank's portfolio of highly leveraged transaction
financings shrank to $4.8 billion at March 31 from $5.3
billion at Dec. 31. But the smaller total still represents
one of the biggest portfolios in the nation -- especially as
a proportion of the bank's total assets of $37 billion.
   The acquisition-finance division's officers, as well as
its assets, have been reassigned to other lending divisions.
Gail Long, who had headed the acquisition-finance division,
has since been put in charge of the larger national division,
handling corporate loans outside New England, a spokesman
said.
   Some of the assets from the acquisition-finance division
were placed in the bank's loan-workout division, the
spokesman said. But he and Mr. Manning insisted that the
proportion of troubled loans wasn't notably high, and that
the quality of the portfolio wasn't a reason for the decision
to disband the division. The division in previous years has
produced strong profits for the company, Mr. Manning said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900522-0132
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900522-0132.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Surging Technology Stocks Dazzle Analysts, Investors
   ----
   By Craig Torres
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/22/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C1
</SO>
<CO>
   CPQ ASTA
</CO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)
SEMICONDUCTORS, INTEGRATED CHIPS (SEM)
SOFTWARE (SOF)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Technology stocks are on a tear.
   Ever since technology companies started reporting
quarterly earnings last month that beat analysts'
expectations, the stocks have rocketed to highs that have
dazzled traders and investors. Indeed, a few analysts are
starting to wonder if technology issues -- computer, software
and semiconductor stocks -- aren't pointing to a further
rally in the stock market.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   By any account, the rally in certain technology stocks has
been astonishing. Compaq Computer Corp. closed at $121.375 a
share yesterday, up $2.75, for a gain of 22% this month
alone. Digital Equipment Corp. closed at $90.625 yesterday,
up $1.375, for a gain on the month of 9.2%. International
Business Machines Corp., once a laggard trading in the low
$90s, added another $1.625 yesterday to close at $117, up
7.3% this month.
   The computer-industry group of the Dow Jones Equity Market
Index is up 18.8% this year, while the overall index is up
only 0.98%.
   The surge in technology issues underscores the point that
1990 is shaping up as a year for growth stocks: issues that
can grow earnings faster than the overall pace of corporate
profits. But technology stocks weren't always romanced by
investors. Late last year, they were dumped.
   Back then, investors thought U.S. demand for new computers
would be sluggish, and they were afraid of
product-development problems at various companies. Compaq
traded below $80 last December.
   But the most recent round of earnings reports showed that
companies such as Compaq are finding strong demand for
computers outside the U.S. Compaq said in its first-quarter
report that international sales made up more than half of its
revenue for the first time.
   Barbara Isgur, vice president at Needham &amp; Co., says the
earnings of computer companies are in a bullish phase. Demand
from Europe should continue, while U.S. corporations are
updating their systems at a faster pace. "Corporations can't
afford to sit still," says Ms. Isgur. They "have to keep pace
with what's acceptable" in terms of computing power.
   Compaq reported first-quarter earnings of $2.13 a share,
about three cents higher than the most-bullish analyst
estimates. Now analysts are boosting their latest estimates
for Compaq and other technology issues. Estimates for Compaq
have been revised upward to $9.31 share for 1990 from $9.11
four months ago, according to the Institutional Brokers
Estimate System, which compiles analysts' forecasts. Analysts
have hiked their 1990 earnings estimates for
personal-computer maker AST Research Inc. to $2.58 a share
from $1.98 four months ago.
   "We see an ebullient market where it's expectations of
earnings rather than asset values driving" stock prices, says
John C. Bogle, Jr., an analyst at State Street Bank and Trust
Co.
   While many growth-stock investors piled into technology
shares months ago, the most recent run in the stocks has been
fueled by so-called value investors. These money managers
roam through thousands of stocks in search of companies whose
shares, by various value benchmarks, are cheaper than the
overall market.
   For the first quarter, these value investors were faced
with the grim choice of bank shares and stocks of some
commodity producers, both considered risky bets when it comes
to earnings. But lately, technology stocks have been popping
up on value investors' computers that search the markets for
cheap stocks.
   Compaq stock, for example, is selling at about 13 times
the computer maker's 1990 earnings forecast, compared with a
price-earnings multiple of about 16 on the Standard &amp; Poor's
500-stock index. "As a value manager, you very rarely get a
chance to buy growth stocks at current multiples," says David
Dreman, president of Dreman Value Management L.P., which owns
about 1.7 million shares of Compaq. Mr. Dreman has 15% of his
$4 billion stock portfolio plunked down in technology issues.
   Now comes the caveat. Technology stocks go down as fast as
they go up. Mr. Bogle says one reason why technology stocks
are trading at a cheaper value than the overall market is
that they are known to be risky. Says Needham's Ms. Isgur:
"There's a hair-trigger in this sector, and that won't
change. It is inevitable that every high technology company
will hit some kind of snag, and in a fair percentage of the
cases it is a four-quarter snag. Investors don't want to hang
around while the problem works out."
   Jack Solomon, technical analyst at Bear, Stearns &amp; Co.,
warns that the stock market looks "frothy" with stocks like
Compaq adding $2 to $3 every day. Still, the romance of high
tech is hard to resist, he says. "When you get technology
stocks going, it infuses the ticker tape with excitement,
attracting the traders and the public," he says. Fast-moving
technology issues "broaden the participation and interest in
the stock market like few other groups can," he says.
</TEXT>
