<HL>
   Kidder to Resume Program Trading
   For Own Account After Six-Month Halt
   ----
   By William Power
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/22/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C25
</SO>
<CO>
   GE BSC MER
</CO>
<IN>
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co., once the biggest
program trader on Wall Street, ended a six-month pullback
from the practice. The action is the latest sign that the
furor over computer-driven trading strategies continues to
wane.
   Kidder, a unit of General Electric Co., was one of six
major brokerage firms that last fall stopped doing
stock-index arbitrage for their own accounts, amid a public
outcry against program trading. Kidder said it resumed the
activity after "extensive conversations" with the New York
Stock Exchange and its own brokers and clients.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Index arbitrage involves rapid-fire trades of big baskets
of stocks with offsetting trades of stock-index futures and
options. It is the most common and controversial form of
program trading. Critics have blamed such computer-driven
trading for big market swings, including the 1987
stock-market crash and the market's sharp plunge Oct. 13.
   Kidder is the second big Wall Street firm to resume index
arbitrage for its own account. Bear Stearns Cos. announced a
similar resumption last December. In the Big Board's latest
weekly statistics, Bear Stearns was the most active Wall
Street program trader -- with an average 2.1 million shares a
day traded in program-trading strategies, almost all of it
involving index arbitrage for its own account. (Kidder was
the fifth-biggest program trader; most of its trades were
index arbitrage for customers.)
   Kidder's decision reflects both the big brokerage firm's
quest for profits -- the firm had a net loss of $23 million
last year -- as well as a reluctance on the part of the Big
Board to take an overly aggressive stand against program
trading. While the Big Board has publicly cautioned brokerage
firms about disruptive program-trading activity, it hasn't
been as forceful as program-trading critics would like.
   Indeed, with overall trading volume on the Big Board off
about 15% from last year's pace, traders are happy for any
volume they can get -- even from program trading.
   A Big Board "blue-ribbon panel" on program trading and
stock-market volatility has been meeting for about five
months, but hasn't yet issued recommendations. Because the
panel isn't expected to recommend a major crackdown on
program trading, brokerage firms apparently don't fear a
backlash from the Big Board if they plunge back into program
activity.
   Letters and phone calls from many of Kidder's 1,400
brokers helped spur Kidder's program pullback last October,
after the Dow Jones Industrial Average plunged 190 points
Oct. 13.
   Charles Sheehan, Kidder's managing director in charge of
retail sales, said that two months ago he asked about 100 of
the firm's top-producing brokers about their current views on
program trading, and "close to 90%" of those responding
supported a resumption of program trading by Kidder. "I think
they understand what we're trying to do is position Kidder as
a leader in developing modern portfolio management
techniques," Mr. Sheehan said.
   In March, Kidder lost its head of customer program
trading, Joseph R. Schmuckler, who joined Nomura Securities
Co. to help Nomura's planned plunge into program trading.
   Thomas F. Ryan, Kidder's executive managing director in
charge of stock trading, said the firm would take a
"controlled, responsible approach" to index arbitrage. "We're
willing to bend over here" to avoid disrupting the markets,
he said.
   Kidder said that in its index arbitrage trading, it would
at all times sell stocks only on "upticks" (when a stock is
rising), and buy only on "downticks." This approach is meant
to avoid accelerating a market move already under way. Kidder
also said it would make data on its index arbitrage activity
available not only to the Big Board but to "other interested
parties."
   A prominent program-trading critic was disturbed by
Kidder's move.
   "These guys aren't helping the financial markets; there's
no way in the world it could help the small investors," said
Charles Wohlstetter, chairman of Contel Corp., a Big
Board-listed company. Mr. Wohlstetter has sharply criticized
the exchange for its program-trading stance and has led a
loose confederation of chief executives campaigning against
program trading in Washington.
   At Merrill Lynch &amp; Co., the nation's biggest brokerage
firm, a spokesman yesterday said, "We continue not to do
index arbitrage for ourselves or for clients," and that there
aren't any plans for resuming the activity.
   ---
   Craig Torres contributed to this article.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
