<HL>
   Economy:
   Budget Surplus
   By U.S. in April
   Was at Record
   ---
   Personal Tax Receipts Cited;
   Surge Was Insufficient
   To Meet Deficit Target
   ----
   By Hilary Stout
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/22/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<IN>
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
ECONOMIC AND MONETARY INDICATORS (EMI)
</IN>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Against the grim backdrop surrounding budget
negotiations between Congress and the Bush administration,
the Treasury offered a snippet of good news yesterday: A
record gush of individual income-tax receipts in April gave
the U.S. a record budget surplus during the month.
   But even the $42.52 billion surplus, larger than many
analysts expected, won't be nearly enough to bring the
deficit to the $100 billion target set by the Gramm-Rudman
law for fiscal 1990 -- or even below last year's $152 billion
gap, many analysts said.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Exceeding the Gramm-Rudman requirements, even by the tens
of billions of dollars now projected, won't bring any
sanctions. The budget process for fiscal 1990, which ends
Oct. 30, is past the point where automatic spending cuts kick
in. But the huge difference between the target and the actual
deficit -- not to mention the likelihood that the deficit
will widen rather than narrow this year -- would emphasize
the failure of that legislation, and of the government budget
efforts in general, to stanch the flow of red ink.
   Still, the numbers suggest that the severe shortfall in
corporate tax receipts this year, stemming from the slowing
economy, hasn't spread to individual income taxes. In April,
receipts from personal income taxes reached $74.38 billion,
surpassing the $68.53 billion collected last April.
   April is a key time to measure individual income taxes,
because the filing deadline for individual taxes falls in the
middle of the month. Because of the deadline, the Treasury
always finishes the month with a bulge of receipts. A quirk
of the calendar also helped enlarge the surplus. The
government pushed into March about $4.5 billion of military
salaries and other payments that were due April 1, which fell
on a Sunday.
   Given all those special factors, Mark Melcher, director of
Washington research at Prudential-Bache Securities, said he
doesn't think the big April surplus "is necessarily great
news."
   April's surplus followed a record monthly deficit in March
of $53.34 billion and narrowed the budget gap for the first
seven months of the fiscal year to $108.34 billion. That
compared with a deficit of $86.98 billion during the
comparable period in fiscal 1989.
   If the Treasury doesn't do any better than it did in the
final five months of fiscal 1989 -- and few economists think
it will -- the fiscal 1990 deficit will exceed $170 billion,
Mr. Melcher said.
   This year, as costs of the government's thrift bailout
program have grown, interest rates have risen and corporate
tax receipts have trailed expectations; private analysts and
even Bush administration officials have steadily enlarged
their estimates of the 1990 budget deficit.
   Adding to the gloomy fiscal outlook is that a good chunk
of the saving-and-loan industry's massive bailout costs
aren't reflected in the budget.
   The Congressional Budget Office now believes the deficit
will reach between $170 billion and $203 billion for fiscal
1990. "Tax collections during the month of April and early
May fell short of our estimates by $15 billion," said Paul
Van der Water, a CBO analyst.
   Kathleen Stephansen, senior economist at Donaldson, Lufkin
&amp; Jenrette, while surprised by the size April's surplus, said
she saw nothing in yesterday's report to change her opinion
that the budget deficit will reach $190 billion this year,
almost twice as much as the Gramm-Rudman deficit-reduction
law mandates.
   Overall, government receipts totaled $139.62 billion last
month, compared with $128.89 billion in April 1989. At the
same time, the government spent $97.11 billion last month,
compared with $88.32 billion in April 1989. The surplus in
April 1989 was $40.57 billion.
   More than $16.5 billion of the outlays last month were
interest payments on the federal debt.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900522-0092
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900522-0092.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   U.S. Has Concerns
   Over Japan's Resolve
   On Trade Initiative
</HL>
<DATE>
05/22/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   JAPAN
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
</IN>
<GV>
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The U.S. is concerned about the strength of
Japan's commitment to the Structural Impediments Initiative
talks, said Charles Dallara, Treasury assistant secretary for
international affairs.
   Senior U.S. and Japanese officials this week meet in
Hawaii to resume the SII talks, a year-long dialogue designed
to break down barriers to a bilateral economic relationship.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "There's some growing concern about the apparent
willingness of the Japanese government to move forward and
make the final SII report a successful report," said Mr.
Dallara, one of the co-heads of the U.S. delegation to
Hawaii. "There are signs of some hesitation and reluctance on
their part."
   The U.S. and Japan on April 5 concluded an interim report
on the SII that both sides heralded as a great success. As
part of that report, Japan agreed to open up its retailing
system, boost public works spending, loosen its clubby
business practices, and strengthen antitrust legislation and
patent protection. Tokyo also said it would relax restrictive
land-use policies and restraints on foreign investment.
   The U.S. promised to encourage savings, improve education,
expand research and development, promote exports and cut the
federal deficit. The April 5 interim agreement, which is
expected to lead to a final SII report in July, was important
to ensuring that Japan avoided being named an unfair trader
under this year's Super 301 determination announced at the
end of April. Super 301 is a tough provision of the 1988
Trade Act that requires the administration to designate
unfair traders whose practices harm U.S. exporters'
prospects.
   The U.S., just a few weeks after letting Japan off the
hook, is now particularly concerned about the issue of
savings and investment. Japan needs "to boost infrastructure
investment," a senior Treasury official explained. There are
also continuing problems with close "keiretsu" links between
Japanese companies, which can promote anticompetitive
business practices and preferential group trade.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900522-0091
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900522-0091.
</DOCID>
