   World Bank Approves
   $96.7 Million in Loans
   For Projects in India
</HL>
<DATE>
05/22/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST
</CO>
<IN>
BANKS (BNK)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The World Bank and its affiliate, the
International Development Association, approved $96.7 million
in loans to India for health centers and population-control
projects in rural areas.
   In other actions, the IDA cleared a $16.1 million credit
to Bolivia to help finance and expand closely held
manufacturing enterprises, and a $14 million loan to Western
Samoa to rebuild roads damaged by a cyclone that hit the
Pacific island nation in February.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The credits, including most of the financing for the
projects in India, will be interest-free except for small
administrative fees. The World Bank will provide $10 million
of the loans to India at a variable interest rate, currently
7.75% a year.
